Based on https://stackoverflow.com/questions/61815948/compilation-error-defining-matxvec3b-2-2-variable-in-opencv
OpenCV 3.4.3 and 4.3.0, on Windows (MSVS14) as well as Ubuntu (gcc 9.3).
Trying to compile the following short piece of code.
```
#include <opencv2/opencv.hpp>

int main()
{
    cv::Matx<cv::Vec3b, 2, 2> good{ cv::Vec3b() };

    cv::Matx<uint8_t, 2, 2> also_good{};

    cv::Matx<cv::Vec3b, 2, 2> bad{};    

    return 0;
}
```
The `bad` statement fails with
```
include\opencv2/core/matx.hpp(540): error C2440: '<function-style-cast>': cannot convert from 'int' to 'cv::Vec3b'
include\opencv2/core/matx.hpp(540): note: No constructor could take the source type, or constructor overload resolution was ambiguous
include\opencv2/core/matx.hpp(539): note: while compiling class template member function 'cv::Matx<cv::Vec3b,2,2>::Matx(void)'
cvtcg.cpp(261): note: see reference to function template instantiation 'cv::Matx<cv::Vec3b,2,2>::Matx(void)' being compiled
cvtcg.cpp(257): note: see reference to class template instantiation 'cv::Matx<cv::Vec3b,2,2>' being compiled
```
I don't see any mention of `Matx` being restricted to primitive types, and don't see any explicit reason why it shouldn't be possible to default initialize such a type.
Is the current behaviour intended (and did I perhaps miss something while reading the documentation), or is this something that should be fixed?

