In my extension FileGroup a user reported an issue: rioj7/fileGroup#6 where the files get loaded in editors but he gets error messages for each file with the text: `Error: Could NOT open editor for "file:///d%3A/dir1/dir2/file.ext".`
All files exist but still a `Could NOT open editor for ` error message is generated.
* If he wants to load 1 file the error message does not happen
* If he wants to load 2 files the error messages **sometimes does NOT** happen
* If he wants to load 3+ files the error messages (most likely) always happen
A slimmed down version of the `extention.js` (before the workaround) is:
```
const vscode = require('vscode');

function activate(context) {
  context.subscriptions.push(vscode.commands.registerCommand('fileGroup.openGroup', async (args) => {
    let column = vscode.ViewColumn.Active;
    let group = { files: [
      "d:\\dir1\\dir2\file1.txt",
      "d:\\dir1\\dir2\file2.txt",
    ]};
    const openFile = filePath => new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
      vscode.window.showTextDocument(vscode.Uri.file(filePath), { preview: false, viewColumn: column }).then( editor => { resolve(true); },
        error => { vscode.window.showErrorMessage(String(error)); reject(error); });
    });
    await Promise.all(group.files.map(openFile));
  }) );
};

function deactivate() {}

module.exports = {
  activate,
  deactivate
}
```
I have wrapped `vscode.window.showTextDocument` in a `Promise` because I do not expect that a `Thenable` will work with `Promise.all()`.
The question is why is the `onrejected` callback of `.then(onfulfilled, onrejeted)` called when the file is loaded in an editor. It only happens when multiple file load Promises are created and waited for. If the function `vscode.window.showTextDocument` performs correct the `.then()` should call the `onfulfilled` callback (no error message).
Can there be some "race" condition internally where multiple calls to `vscode.window.showTextDocument` manipulate some global data that is not guarded by some "mutex"? Because with 2 files it sometimes happens.
The workaround is to replace
```
    await Promise.all(group.files.map(openFile));
```
with serial loading of the files
```
    for (const file of group.files) { await openFile(file).catch( () => {} ); }
```

.git is being appended to the names of files internally, when their filenames are accessed via the extension api.
because vscode insists on throwing file open and file close events `for tab switching` i have to compare the file that was closed to the list of files code is still keeping open, after a delay, so code asyncly has time to actually attempt to close it.
because code is appending this weird ".git" to the end it is never finding the file.
```javascript
for(Iter = 0; Iter < vscode.workspace.textDocuments.length; Iter++) {
	AutoFoldTracker.PrintDebug("file to check: " + File.uri.fsPath);
	AutoFoldTracker.PrintDebug("currently open: " + vscode.workspace.textDocuments[Iter].uri.fsPath);

	if(vscode.workspace.textDocuments[Iter].uri.fsPath == File.uri.fsPath)
	return;
}
```
